                    Exam AZ-900 Microsoft Azure Fundamentals
                    Course Notes Part 7


10.2 Describe Azure Key Vault
  - It is secure storage of secrets, keys and certificates
  - There is a standard and premium pricing tier
    - Premium tier access keys are stored in Hardware Security Modules
    - The premium tier is required for compliance such as FIPS 140-2

10.3 Describe Azure Information Protection
  - Important or sensitive information may not always be in your control
    - You may want to send an email for example that contains sensitive information that you wish to control
    - For that situation you can use Azure Information Protection
    - This is designed to protect emails and Office documents
    - Emails can be classified as Public, Confidential, Highly Confidential etc
      - Protection can then be applied
 
10.4 Describe Azure Advanced Threat Protection
- Azure Security Center
    - This is a single portal for monitoring and managing security
    - Security Center agent allows for on-premises resources
    - There are 2 tiers of service available
      - Free which covers VM's and App Service only
      - Standard which covers VM's, App Service, Databases, PostGreSQL, MySQL and blob storage



Lesson 11: Learn Azure Governance Methodologies
11.1 Describe Azure Policy
  - As well as security concern there are going to be governance concerns
  - Azure Policy is a tool for enforcing policies
    - A policy can be not having a type of resource within a region etc
    - It is used to define and enforce rules for resource creation and management
    - It uses policies to define rules
  - One of the aspects of policy is called effect
    - If the effect is Audit then a non-complicance warning is logged
    - There are 5 other effects
      - Append which adds additional properties to a policy
      - AuditIfNotExists logs a warning if a resource type does not already exist
      - Deny effect will deny the create or update operation
      - DeployIfNotExists automatically deploys a specific resource type if it does not alread exist
      - Disabled mean that the policy is not in effect

11.2 Describe Role-based Access Control
  - Azure Role-based Access Control
    - This authorises users based on their role
    - There are 4 elements
      - Security Principal
        - This represents an identity, it can be a user, group etc
